## Observed Claims

- Gravity is described as a local-first universal evidence-ingestion platform
  that discovers heterogeneous files, preserves unique byte sequences, extracts
  replayable provenance-rich structure, manifests human-readable projections,
  and exposes searchable/citable knowledge to humans and agents.
- Gravity's draft product principles include preserve before transform, source
  occurrence distinct from exact artifact, no silent omission, canonical
  structure before Markdown, evidence before narrative, ACL/classification
  propagation, immutable/rebuildable generations, local-first processing, and
  measured quality/cost/privacy/provenance.
- The MVP horizon is an NFS-root-to-evidence loop with polling/reconciliation
  discovery, exact SHA-256 preservation, universal baseline extraction, selected
  specialist processing, vault/index projection, non-blocking review
  visibility, and permission-aware retrieval.
- Gravity's architecture overview frames the system as a content-addressed,
  provenance-preserving, permission-aware knowledge supply chain with a control
  plane for configuration, state, registries, policies, run ledger, active
  pointers, audit, cost, and review.
- The architecture draft proposes a walking skeleton with NFS/NAS root,
  polling crawler, lowercase SHA-256 identity, S3-compatible storage,
  PostgreSQL catalog/run/control authority, and PostgreSQL outbox plus leased
  work queue as planning defaults pending review.
- LangGraph is explicitly constrained: it may define deterministic per-content
  workflow and modality subgraphs, but must not become the asset database,
  artifact store, work queue, run ledger, model registry, or review gate.
- The pipeline state machine requires explicit, auditable, contract-tested
  transitions, with workers requesting transitions while the control plane or
  owning module records authoritative state.
- Human review in Gravity's pipeline is modeled as review records and later
  actions; it should not leave the main automated pipeline indefinitely waiting.
- Gravity CI/CD planning treats CI/CD as the enforcement layer for docs-as-code,
  contract-first development, security, lane integration, release evidence,
  provenance, SBOMs, vulnerability scans, migrations, smoke tests, and rollback
  paths.
- Gravity's status document records a draft planning baseline, no observed
  product implementation, no runtime/deployment evidence, empty GitHub issues at
  last check, draft issue bodies, proposed lane contracts, and an open human
  decision gate for the documentation planning pass.
- Gravity's repository instructions still default execution to one issue, lane,
  branch, worktree, worker session, and pull request, with human gates for API,
  schema/frontmatter, storage/retention, security boundary, destructive data,
  external dependency, and deployment-risk changes.

